VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or gray frames have been added in the&nbsp; middle of the 2 clips for transitioning. Next, we will need to re-check our text encoder&nbsp; nodes. If you choose to use the GGUF node,&nbsp;&nbsp; just drag the output and connect it here. Then,&nbsp; connect both positive and negative outputs like&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'so, as shown here. If you choose to use the API,&nbsp; just enable the group and connect them like so.&nbsp;&nbsp; I prefer to bypass the nodes I do not use so it&nbsp; becomes easier for me to debug the flow if needed.&nbsp;'

[06:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Last thing we need to do before we can run the&nbsp; workflow is to set the audio input. According to&nbsp;&nbsp; the dev, it is recommended that we use an&nbsp; audio reference for the video, as strange&nbsp;&nbsp; artifacts might occur when processing with this&nbsp; LoRA. First, we load our audio via this node. We&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can then crop the audio with this node. It does&nbsp; not have to be the same length as the video.&nbsp;&nbsp; Audio will be added to the whole video, if the&nbsp; audio is not shorter than the video length.'

[07:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I have included 2 nodes for audio crop&nbsp; for you to use. They are essentially the&nbsp;&nbsp; same. I have mostly color coded the&nbsp; nodes for easy identification. So,&nbsp;&nbsp; you just need to connect the audio latent you&nbsp; want to use. Dark blue is for ref audio input,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and light blue is for LTX audio generation. The prompt enhancer or generator can be&nbsp;&nbsp; very handy. Gemma 4 will scan through the merged&nbsp; video and generates the description of each clip,&nbsp;&nbsp; as well as the transitions, according&nbsp; to the system prompt from the dev.'

